      "news": [
        {
          "key": "sage-intacct-2026-04-27-sage-brings-planning-spend-cash-flow-hcm-and-industry-workflows-into-sage-intacct",
          "date": "2026-04-27",
          "type": "product-release",
          "headline": "Sage brings planning, spend, cash flow, HCM, and industry workflows into Sage Intacct",
          "buyerRelevance": "Shows Sage Intacct moving from accounting toward connected finance operations and vertical workflows.",
          "sourceLabel": "Sage Press",
          "sourceUrl": "https://www.sage.com/en-us/news/press-releases/2026/04/sage-brings-core-finance-and-industry-workflows-together-in-sage-intacct/",
          "submitter": "G2 research",
          "status": "accepted",
          "sourceNote": "Official Sage product announcement with module and availability details.",
          "article": "Sage announced new Sage Intacct capabilities across planning, spend, cash flow, HCM, and industry workflows in an [official product release](https://www.sage.com/en-us/news/press-releases/2026/04/sage-brings-core-finance-and-industry-workflows-together-in-sage-intacct/).\n\nThe headline is breadth. Sage Intacct is being positioned less like a standalone accounting system and more like a connected finance operating layer. That matters for buyers who want subscription billing and revenue workflows to land in a finance system that also handles planning, spend control, cash visibility, and vertical requirements.\n\n- Buyer signal: Sage is expanding Intacct's connected-finance story, which can reduce the number of systems around the general ledger.\n- Follow-up: Confirm availability by region and edition, integration depth between modules, and whether industry workflows fit the buyer's exact revenue model."
        },
        {
          "key": "sage-intacct-2026-04-21-sage-and-pwc-launch-agentic-ai-delivery-model-for-sage-intacct-implementations",
          "date": "2026-04-21",
          "type": "implementation-partnership",
          "headline": "Sage and PwC launch agentic AI delivery model for Sage Intacct implementations",
          "buyerRelevance": "Implementation speed, consistency, and time-to-value are major ERP selection risks for finance buyers.",
          "sourceLabel": "Sage Press",
          "sourceUrl": "https://www.sage.com/en-us/news/press-releases/2026/04/sage-and-pwc-use-agentic-ai-to-get-sage-intacct-finance-teams-up-and-running-faster/",
          "submitter": "G2 research",
          "status": "accepted",
          "sourceNote": "Official Sage release naming PwC and describing the implementation model.",
          "article": "Sage and PwC announced an [agentic AI delivery model](https://www.sage.com/en-us/news/press-releases/2026/04/sage-and-pwc-use-agentic-ai-to-get-sage-intacct-finance-teams-up-and-running-faster/) for Sage Intacct implementations.\n\nThis is buyer-relevant because ERP implementation risk is often more important than feature checklists. If the delivery model can improve consistency, setup speed, or migration quality, it may reduce time-to-value for finance teams. The practical question is whether the AI-assisted approach changes outcomes, not just whether it sounds modern.\n\n- Buyer signal: Implementation acceleration is a real selection factor for finance buyers comparing ERP and accounting platforms.\n- Follow-up: Ask for proof points on deployment time, data migration quality, controls, partner responsibilities, and post-launch support."
        },
        {
          "key": "sage-intacct-2026-02-17-sage-intacct-adds-finance-intelligence-close-analytics-cash-intelligence-ap-matching-and-data-cloud",
          "date": "2026-02-17",
          "type": "product-release",
          "headline": "Sage Intacct adds finance intelligence, close analytics, cash intelligence, AP matching, and Data Cloud",
          "buyerRelevance": "Strong signal for finance teams evaluating AI-assisted close, cash forecasting, AP automation, and live data access.",
          "sourceLabel": "Sage Press",
          "sourceUrl": "https://www.sage.com/en-us/news/press-releases/2026/02/sage-intacct-delivers-new-ai-powered-capabilities-to-transform-how-finance-teams-close/",
          "submitter": "G2 research",
          "status": "accepted",
          "sourceNote": "Official Sage press release with feature-by-feature availability notes.",
          "article": "Sage announced AI-powered capabilities for Sage Intacct, including finance intelligence, close analytics, cash intelligence, AP matching, and Data Cloud, in an [official Sage release](https://www.sage.com/en-us/news/press-releases/2026/02/sage-intacct-delivers-new-ai-powered-capabilities-to-transform-how-finance-teams-close/).\n\nFor buyers, the interesting point is the combination of close, cash, AP, and data access. Those workflows sit close to subscription billing because invoices, collections, revenue, and cash forecasting all need trusted finance data. Sage is signaling that Intacct should help finance teams analyze and act, not only record transactions.\n\n- Buyer signal: Useful for organizations that want billing-adjacent finance automation and live data access in the accounting layer.\n- Follow-up: Review feature availability, audit controls, exception handling, and how AI recommendations are surfaced inside close and cash workflows."
        }
      ],
